article.description:
The Connecticut Sun dominated the New York
Liberty again. This time, they left no room for a comeback.
article.headline: Sun end three-game skid against Liberty
article.linkText: Sun don't waste lead this time against Liberty
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Connecticut Sun dominated the New York Liberty again. This time, they left no room for a comeback.

The Sun posted an 84-71 victory over the defending Eastern Conference champion Liberty on Saturday. The victory moved the Sun within a half-game of third-place Cleveland with four to play. New York fell into sixth place.

Only the top four teams in each conference make the playoffs.

Connecticut (15-15) blew a 17-point lead and lost 74-73 to the Liberty on Tuesday. The Sun didn't let up this time.

Nykesha Sales scored 22 points to lead the Sun, who led by as 15 points in the first half and finished the half shooting 57 percent (17-for-30) from the field. The Sun shot 51 percent (27-for-53) for the game as they snapped a three-game losing streak.

"This is a great win," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said. "We were resilient and we came out ready to play."

Connecticut and New York (13-16) had their respective games on Thursday postponed due to the blackout that affected the Northeast, Ohio and Canada. The Sun's game at Cleveland will be made up on Tuesday, while the Liberty's home game against Houston was rescheduled for Monday.

The Sun arrived at Madison Square Garden an hour and a half before the game after a 16½-hour bus ride back from Cleveland. But they didn't appear weary.

"We knew how important this game was," Johnson said. "Unfortunately, we weren't able to play the Cleveland game because of the blackout. But, we were playing a team that we just lost by a point."

New York had won four of six.

Vickie Johnson led New York with 19 points, with 10 coming in the second half. Tamika Whitmore added 13 points and Tari Phillips chipped in 12 for the Liberty, who shot 46 percent (27-of-59) for the game.

"It was a big game for us," Whitmore said. "We just have to put this behind us and get back into the swing of things."

The Sun led 40-29 at the half, and maintained their double-digit advantage the rest of the way.

Connecticut's reserves outscored New York's substitutes 36-18. Wendy Palmer led the way with 20 points for the Sun, who finished the game shooting 51 percent (27-for-53).

"We let their bench kill us," New York forward Crystal Robinson said. "We have to play a little harder and do different things as a team."

With the interrupted schedule, the Liberty will be playing three games in as many days. This is the first time in WNBA history that this will occur. The last time an NBA team played three consecutive games in three days was during the 1998-99 lockout season.

"It is just one game at a time and we just have to find the energy to play and win," Robinson added.

The Liberty will visit Cleveland on Sunday, then return to face the Comets on Monday. New York is 1-4 in the second of back-to-back games this season.

The Liberty are 2-9 all-time at Gund Arena, including a 74-50 season-opening loss on May 31.

"Tomorrow will be difficult, because Cleveland is a difficult place to win," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. "Somehow we have to find a way to steal that game tomorrow."
